## 1. What We Are Building (One Paragraph)

BillConnect is a **translation layer between UK commerce language and structured product identity**. It takes messy retail transaction strings — e.g. `TSCO S/S MLK 2L` — and resolves them into clean, structured product records (canonical name, category, nutrition, ingredients, allergens, price history). On top of that core engine sit two products: **SwipeBin** (consumer home-inventory and grocery management app) and a **B2B API** that sells the resolution + enrichment capability to other apps.

---

## 2. The Core Problem

UK retail transaction strings are unreadable to software. A bank feed, receipt scan, or open-banking record shows `TSCO S/S MLK 2L` — which means nothing to an app trying to categorise spending or surface nutrition. Existing public data sources are incomplete:

- **Open Food Facts (UK):** ~41% of products have a Nutriscore; ingredient coverage is patchy for retail SKUs; own-brand items are frequently missing entirely.
- **Apify / generic scrapers:** return prices and names, rarely structured nutrition/ingredients; fragile against site changes.
- **Commercial DBs (Nutritionix, FatSecret):** US-heavy, expensive, weak on UK discount retailers (Aldi, Iceland, Lidl).

The defensible asset is **not** the scraping or the nutrition data. It is the **identity resolution** — consistently mapping dirty strings to one canonical product, deterministically enough that a fintech pipeline can depend on it.

---

## 3. System Architecture (Two Separate Systems)

A recurring design principle: **keep the offline intelligence separate from the online product.** Do not merge them.

| Layer | Job | Owner | Online/Offline |
|---|---|---|---|
| Normalisation | Clean messy text (lowercase, units, noise) | Us | Online |
| Alias expansion | `tsco`→`tesco`, `s/s`→`semi skimmed` | Us | Online |
| Candidate generation | Fast retrieval (BM25 / token overlap) | Us | Online |
| Ranking | Hybrid weighted scoring | Us | Online |
| Confidence gating | Accept / low-confidence / reject | Us | Online |
| Product ID output | Stable contract for consumers | Us | Online |
| Enrichment | Nutrition, ingredients, allergens | OFF / scrapers | Online (post-match) |
| Alias discovery | Cluster strings → alias dictionaries | Us | **Offline** |
| Dataset cleanup | Dedup, taxonomy, quality audit | Us | **Offline** |

### 3.1 Online Resolver Pipeline

```
INPUT  "TSCO S/S MLK 2L"
  → 1. Normalisation       (deterministic, cheap)
  → 2. Alias expansion     (real accuracy leverage)
  → 3. Candidate generation (BM25 / inverted index — top 5–20)
  → 4. Ranking             (token sim + alias + embedding + retailer)
  → 5. Confidence gate      (>0.85 accept / 0.6–0.85 low / <0.6 no match)
  → 6. Product ID output    (stable JSON contract)
  → 7. Enrichment           (OFF / scrape — OPTIONAL, post-match)
OUTPUT structured product record
```

**Algorithm stance:**
- Core resolver = **retrieval + ranking**, NOT clustering. Use BM25, Jaro-Winkler / Levenshtein, alias expansion, weighted scoring, probabilistic thresholding (Fellegi-Sunter is the closest academic model).
- **No** K-means / Agglomerative / DBSCAN in the live path — those are offline-only.
- Avoid LLM calls in the core path. Fintech consumers want determinism and stable outputs.

### 3.2 Offline Intelligence (clustering belongs here)

Clustering (K-means, Agglomerative, embeddings) is valuable but **offline only**:
- Alias discovery — group `s/s milk`, `semi skim milk`, `semi skimmed milk` → generate alias rules.
- Product deduplication across retailers.
- Taxonomy / category normalisation.

---

## 4. The Moat

> Resolving `TSCO S/S MLK 2L` correctly, consistently, and deterministically.

Everything else — OFF, Apify, scraping — is **gap-filling after identity is solved**. If scraping or a third-party nutrition source becomes central, the product becomes a low-moat wrapper that is trivial to replicate. The resolver + the proprietary alias dictionary + the cleaned UK retail dataset are the defensible core.

